    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Contact Precautions", content: "Contact precautions are implemented to prevent transmission of infectious agents spread by direct contact (touching the patient's skin or body fluids) or indirect contact (touching contaminated environmental surfaces or equipment). Organisms requiring contact precautions include multidrug-resistant organisms (MRSA, VRE, CRE, ESBL-producing bacteria), Clostridioides difficile (spore-forming, resistant to alcohol-based sanitizers — requires soap and water handwashing), respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), and ectoparasites (scabies, lice). The nurse must don a gown and gloves before entering the patient's room, use dedicated equipment (stethoscope, blood pressure cuff, thermometer) or disinfect shared equipment between patients, and perform hand hygiene upon removal of PPE. Contact isolation can negatively affect patient well-being through decreased healthcare worker visits, increased anxiety and depression, and reduced patient satisfaction — the nurse should maintain therapeutic communication, explain the rationale for precautions, and ensure patients receive adequate psychosocial support." },
